\f0\b\fs56 \cf0 Dark Cherry Liqueur I\

\b0\fs50 Step One Ingredients:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1 1/2 lbs fresh or frozen cherries\
{\listtext	\'95	}Cherry pits from half of the cherries (from 3/4 lb)\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 1/4 cup sugar (see notes below)\
{\listtext	\'95	}750 ml 80-proof vodka\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Step One Directions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}If using fresh cherries, pit the cherries with a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.homebrewunderground.com/equipment/#cherry_pitter"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 cherry pitter}} and save the pits. If using frozen cherries, thaw them first.\
{\listtext	2.	}Put cherries and sugar in 2 Qt. Mason jar.\
{\listtext	3.	}Add vodka then shake thoroughly to dissolve the sugar.\
{\listtext	4.	}Crack open the cherry pits and chop the kernels with a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.homebrewunderground.com/equipment/#chopper"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 chopper}}, then add them to the mixture.\
{\listtext	5.	}Macerate at room temperature for 8 weeks.\
\pard\tx560\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Step Two Ingredients:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1/2 cup {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.homebrewunderground.com/sugar-syrup/#sugar_syrup"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 standard sugar syrup}}\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Step Two Directions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Strain through a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.homebrewunderground.com/equipment/#strainers"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 stainless steel strainer}} to separate cherries from vodka and juice. (see notes below)\
{\listtext	2.	}Squeeze the remaining juice from the separated cherries using cheese cloth. (see notes below)\
{\listtext	3.	}Add the sugar syrup. Vary the amount to sweeten to taste.\
{\listtext	4.	}Age for 2 to 3 months\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Notes:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\ql\qnatural
\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}Use only very ripe, juicy cherries. If cherries are not ripe enough, then let them stand until as ripe and juicy as they can get.\
{\listtext	\'95	}You can use 1 1/2 cups of sugar instead of 1 1/4 cups and possibly skip the addition of standard sugar syrup at step 2. It depends on the sweetness of the fruit. You should always sample the flavor when sweetening.\
{\listtext	\'95	}If you crush the cherries at step one, then macerate for only 4 weeks. This will make a lot of sediment, though, depending on the degree that the cherries are crushed. The finished liqueur will have to stand in a Mason jar for about 4 more weeks to clarify, then you will have to rack off the clarified liqueur before bottling.\
\pard\tx560\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 \
