\b\fs54 \cf0 Straining The Liqueur\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs50 \cf0 In this straining step, you need a common kitchen {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.homebrewunderground.com/equipment/#strainers"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 stainless steel strainer}} and some food grade cheese cloth.
\b\fs54 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\ql\qnatural

\b0\fs50 \cf0 The first step in straining the liqueur is to pour all the contents from the Mason Jar into the strainer over a saucepan or pot. All the cherries will collect in the strainer. Empty the saucepan or pot and pour the juice and vodka mixture into a clean Mason Jar.\
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 Add some of the cherries to a piece of cheesecloth and gently squeeze them so the juice collects in the saucepan or pot:\
\pard\tx560\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\ql\qnatural
\cf0 When all the juice has been squeezed out of the cheese cloth, pour it into the Mason Jar. Repeat this process on small batches of the cherries until all the juice is squeezed out.\
\
Now set the Mason Jar aside in a cool place and let it age for 2 to 3 months. During this time, sediments will settle to the bottom of the jar. At some point, rack off the clarified liqueur leaving the "sludge" or "slag" behind in the jar. When the time comes to bottle the liqueur, bottle only the clearest liqueur. This is the best quality. A good explanation of "racking" can be found at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.guntheranderson.com/liqueurs/filters.htm"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 Gunther Anderson\'92s website on making liqueur}}.\
